statement.p:
Let f(x) = b^{x} be an exponential function (b > 0, b\neq 1) and let u and w be real numbers. exponential functionalgebraic properties of
Product Rule: product rulefor exponential functions f(u+w) = f(u) f(w). In other words, b^{u+w} = b^{u} b^{w}
Quotient Rule: quotient rulefor exponential functions f(u-w) = \dfrac{f(u)}{f(w)}. In other words, b^{u-w} = \dfrac{b^{u}}{b^{w}}
Power Rule: power rulefor exponential functions \left(f(u)\right)^w = f(uw). In other words, \left(b^{u}\right)^{w} = b^{uw}

li.p:
To expand \log_{2}\left(\frac{8}{x}\right),
we use the Quotient Rule identifying u = 8 and w=x and simplify.

  \log_{2}\left(\dfrac{8}{x}\right) \amp  =   \log_{2}(8) - \log_{2}(x) \tag{Quotient Rule}
  \amp  =   3 - \log_{2}(x)  \tag{Since $2^{3} = 8$}
  \amp  =  - \log_{2}(x) + 3

      In Theorem,
      there is no mention of how to deal with radicals.
      However,
thinking back to Definition,
      we can rewrite the cube root as a \frac{1}{3} exponent.
      We begin by using the Power Rule,
      and we keep in mind that the common log is log base 10.




          At this point in the text,
          the reader is encouraged to carefully read through each step and think of which quantity is playing the role of u and which is playing the role of w as we apply each property.



        \log \sqrt[3]{\dfrac{100 x^2}{yz^5}} \amp  =  \log \left(\dfrac{100 x^2}{yz^5}\right)^{1/3}
        \amp  =  \frac{1}{3} \log\left(\dfrac{100 x^2}{yz^5}\right)  \tag{Power Rule}
        \amp  =  \frac{1}{3} \left[ \log\left(100x^2\right) - \log\left(yz^5\right) \right]  \tag{Quotient Rule}
        \amp  = \frac{1}{3}\log\left(100x^2\right) - \frac{1}{3}\log\left(yz^5\right)
        \amp  =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ \log(100) + \log\left(x^2\right)\right] - \frac{1}{3} \left[ \log(y) + \log\left(z^5\right) \right]  \tag{Product Rule}
        \amp  = \frac{1}{3} \log(100) + \frac{1}{3} \log\left(x^2\right) - \frac{1}{3} \log(y) - \frac{1}{3} \log\left(z^5\right)
        \amp  =  \frac{1}{3} \log(100) + \frac{2}{3} \log(x) - \frac{1}{3} \log(y) - \frac{5}{3} \log(z)  \tag{Power Rule}
        \amp  =  \frac{2}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \log(x) - \frac{1}{3} \log(y) - \frac{5}{3} \log(z)  \tag{Since $10^2=100$}
        \amp  =   \frac{2}{3} \log(x) - \frac{1}{3} \log(y) - \frac{5}{3} \log(z) + \frac{2}{3}
